<TEXT>
five police intelligence officers were 
released early saturday after kashmiri moslem separatists pulled 
them from a jeep at gunpoint the day before a state governor said 
on friday a cabinet minister acknowledging the moslem 
rebellion had reached an unprecedented point said the 
government was opening negotiations with the separatists 
the governor said the five men were released unharmed after 
government loudspeakers blared allnight warnings that strong 
action would be taken if the kidnapped officers were not freed 
our approach of firmness in dealing with the terrorists 
worked said gov jagmohan of jammukashmir state he said the 
five men members of the jammukashmir state police intelligence 
branch reappeared before sunrise in the same area they were 
abducted friday night 
no claims of responsibility or demands were made on behalf of 
the abductors 
the five men had been in a jeep patrolling a congested 
residential area in the heart of srinagar core of the movement 
demanding mostly moslem kashmirs independence from predominantly 
hindu india 
a curfew was in effect but a crowd surrounded the intelligence 
officers jeep jagmohan said he said three young men took the 
officers from the jeep at gunpoint and set fire to the vehicle 
jagmohan had said friday that only four agents were missing the 
agency united news of india had said the missing agents working in 
security units for senior government officials 
earlier friday railway minister george fernandes told reporters 
the government was opening talks with the separatists 
it is too early to say what shape the dialogue will take but 
at least the process has begun he said 
fernandes selected by the government of prime minister vp 
singh to initiate the talks said he was meeting the right 
people through intermediaries but he said we have a tough 
job here 
islamic militants have been fighting for secession of 
jammukashmir state from india for the last four decades the 
latest round of violence began jan 20 after a government crackdown 
on the militants at least 173 people have been killed and hundreds 
injured since then 
a highlevel political delegation comprising leaders of all 
major parties visited srinagar on thursday to assess the 
situation the team returned to new delhi on friday but fernandes 
who was part of the delegation stayed back apparently to initiate 
the dialogue 
srinagar is summer capital of jammukashmir state 
the mood of the people is very obvious the campaign for 
secession has reached an unprecedented point he said friday 
it was not known who the government would negotiate with the 
militants said earlier they will not negotiate their demand for 
independence 
in neighboring pakistanheld kashmir about 500 demonstrators 
demanded selfdetermination for their brethren in india during a 
protest march friday to a pakistani military checkpoint along the 
border 
protesters shouted death to vp singh and indian dogs 
go home but no violence was reported 
kashmir once a fabled tourist area is in far northern india 
about 400 miles north of new delhi 
it has been under dispute between india and pakistan since 1948 
when the hindu ruler of the former princely state decided to merge 
with india since then moslemdominated pakistan and india have 
twice gone to war over the region 
the us state department on friday warned americans to avoid 
indian airlines flights to srinagar because of the possibility of 
terrorist attacks it said in a statement the warning was prompted 
by posters that appeared in the srinagar area telling people not to 
take the airlines flights to the city 
</TEXT>
