<DOCNO> AP900310-0009 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a presidential commission is trying to find 
out how many people changed travel plans when the us embassy in 
moscow disseminated a terrorism warning before the 1988 bombing of 
pan american flight 103 
two embassy witnesses testified under oath friday that a notice 
from the federal aviation administration of bomb threats against 
pan am flights en route to the united states was posted in several 
places around the diplomatic compound and outside and also was sent 
to soviet officials 
the state department previously acknowledged only that the 
notice was improperly posted in the embassy a week before flight 
103 blew up over lockerbie scotland killing 270 people on dec 
21 1988 
officials said the posting violated a policy against notifying 
government personnel when others are not told of a threat 
the embassy notice said employees were left to their own 
discretion on whether to change travel plans but it noted they 
still were required to fly on an american airline pan am was the 
only us carrier serving moscow although other airlines could be 
used from europe to the united states 
raymond f smith who was acting deputy chief of mission in 
moscow at the time told the presidential commission on aviation 
security and terrorism that he felt a moral obligation to let 
people know about the threat against pan am flights between 
frankfurt west germany and the united states 
i said to myself would i want my own family to take the 
information into account and the answer was yes smith said 
justifying the decision to inform all embassy personnel and other 
people who might fly of the threat 
smith said he knew of no other embassy that disseminated the 
notice publicly state department officials have said the threat 
turned out to be a hoax originating in helsinki finland 
embassy officials decided in a toplevel staff meeting to give 
the notice the widest distribution possible smith and embassy 
security officer mark a sanna testified 
at fridays hearing the commission disclosed a telex message 
from pan ams moscow office saying that 80 percent of the airlines 
moscow passengers were changing their bookings as a result of the 
posted threat 
but jennifer s young the airlines former moscow manager who 
sent the telex testified that she had no direct knowledge of any 
cancellations and used the 80 percent figure to give her telex some 
impact because she needed advice on what to tell travelers 
ms young said a parttime reservations clerk at pan ams office 
in the us embassy had told her there were several inquiries about 
the notice and she got the impression there also were cancellations 
commission chairwoman ann mclaughlin said the panel staff has 
yet to find hard evidence of any changes in bookings as a result of 
the threat but has asked pan am for passenger data and is 
continuing its investigation 
relatives of some of the victims of the flight 103 bombing have 
questioned the fact that the plane a boeing 747 jumbo jet had 
more than 160 empty seats even though the flight was during a busy 
holiday period they say they believe government personnel 
cancelled because of the selective warning 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

