<TEXT>
the state house approved a bill that would 
outlaw abortion as a method of birth control and provide the 
nations strongest challenge to a 1973 supreme court ruling 
legalizing abortion 
were really excited nancy myers a spokeswoman for 
national right to life committee in washington dc said after 
fridays 4736 vote we consider it to be extremely significant 
the measure was forwarded to the senate after more than three 
hours of debate before a gallery packed with activists from both 
sides of the issue 
the bill could come to a final senate floor vote as early as 
friday and opponents said it stood a good chance of passing the 
gop controls both houses of the legislature 
the bill like legislation rejected recently in minnesota and 
utah would outlaw abortion as a method of birth control it would 
allow abortions only in cases of rape incest profound and 
irremediable fetal disabilities or to save the life or prevent 
severe and longlasting physical health damage to the mother 
sponsors contend that would prevent more than 90 percent of some 
1600 abortions performed each year in idaho 
penalties of up to 10000 for a first offense 30000 for a 
second and 50000 for each additional violation could be assessed 
against any physician performing or attempting to perform an 
abortion women undergoing the procedure would not be legally 
responsible 
gov cecil andrus has yet to comment on the bill but he has 
come out strongly against abortion in most cases 
along with a 1989 pennsylvania law which has been partially 
blocked by a federal court injunction the idaho bill would be the 
most restrictive in the nation according to its sponsors and the 
national right to life committee 
im just so proud that idahoans are taking the lead in 
returning protection to our unborn children said kerry 
uhlenkott legislative coordinator for right to life of idaho inc 
the supreme court is inviting us to send up legislation and 
thats what were doing 
advocates of legalized abortion were disappointed that 
legislators ignored arguments the measure would fail to pass 
constitutional muster and that most idaho residents want the 
legislature to stay out of the issue 
i consistently heard the word morality used always ascribed 
to the life of the unborn said sally trott of freedom means 
choice i never heard it used in reference to the states 
obligation if its going to coerce a woman to carry a pregnancy to 
term 
on thursday the house approved and sent the senate legislation 
repealing the states controversial trigger law which sets 
criminal penalties including prison terms up to five years both for 
physicians and women receiving abortions 
the statute would have taken effect only if the us supreme 
court completely overturned its 1973 roe vs wade decision 
legalizing abortion during the first two trimesters of pregnancy 
after nearly 17 years of relative inactivity on abortion idaho 
got back into the fray after last julys us supreme court ruling 
in a missouri case webster vs reproductive health services which 
gave states greater freedom to set limits on abortion 
opponents of the bill cited richard wilkins a brigham young 
university law professor who advised the utah legislature against 
similar legislation 
wilkins opposes abortion but contends the birth control bill 
goes too far in challenging the supreme courts stand and would be 
found unconstitutional on a number of grounds including the test 
that state restrictions should not impose an undue burden on 
the mother 
i am honestly and genuinely convinced that if we pass this 
bill it will hurt the prolife movement that it will be struck 
down said democratic rep patricia mcdermott 
but the bills sponsors said it balances privacy concerns and 
the states responsibility to intervene 
how can any act that involves the consent of one party the 
participation of a second and the destruction of a third be a 
purely private matter asked house majority leader gary 
montgomery 
</TEXT>
