<TEXT>
the united states risks losing its 
international partners in the manned space station project if 
congress cuts back on the 26 billion requested for the project in 
1991 nasa administrator richard h truly says 
i think a major reduction would cause them to look very 
seriously at our commitment to the project truly told the senate 
science technology and space subcommittee friday 
the space station freedom is part of the bush administrations 
151 billion request for space programs in fiscal 1991 which 
begins oct 1 the project with european japanese and canadian 
partners has been called the largest international research and 
development enterprise ever undertaken 
relations with the project partners were strained by the united 
states decision last year to delay completion of construction for 
one year without consulting them 
the administration blamed the delay on congressional funding 
cuts and design changes even though the 200 million cut was half 
as large as the administration first alleged 
the european space agency complained that its projects were 
given a back seat in the new plans 
truly said the project scheduled for the first launch in five 
years and permanent manning capability in 1999 is critical for 
further exploration of space especially the moon and mars 
the national aeronautics and space administrations budget 
request is 23 percent higher than the 1990 spending plan and the 
administration expects to call for similar increases in 1992 and 
1993 
subcommittee chairman albert gore jr dtenn questioned the 
feasibility of getting that much money 
gore also suggested nasa might be biting off more projects than 
it can chew leaving many open to the risk of underfunding during 
critical years space projects tend to have lower startup costs 
the dollar amounts begin to balloon the farther along the projects 
get 
gore also raised the issue of the space station when he asked 
truly whether the foreign partners were willing to sit still for 
a further whittling away at the station project a reference to 
previous budget cuts 
the 1991 request for the space station represents a 36 percent 
or 699 million increase over the 1990 amount 
this is a critical time for the space station truly said 
the program is transitioning from the preliminary design to the 
fabrication and testing of development hardware 
he said all major contractors are on board as are many of the 
subcontractors 
addressing the overall nasa budget gore questioned the 
administrations economic assumptions behind it economic growth 
capital gains tax reduction more user fees and lower interest 
rates 
there is still an air of unreality in the administrations 
approach to the budget gore said 
</TEXT>
