<TEXT>
the senate is taking a weeklong respite from 
its cleanair debate as lawmakers and the white house try to work 
out an agreement on providing help to coal miners made jobless by 
stricter pollution controls 
unable to resolve the dispute majority leader george mitchell 
dmaine canceled plans friday to continue consideration of the 
clean air legislation into the weekend 
the senate instead adjourned for a previously scheduled recess 
until march 20 when mitchell said the bill will be the first 
order of business 
senate leaders had been prepared thursday to bring the coal 
miner amendment offered by sen robert byrd dwva to a vote 
but action was postponed when they grew uncertain about their 
strength to defeat the proposal 
the amendment is one of a string of proposed changes that would 
significantly alter the compromise reached between senate leaders 
and the white house in private negotiations senate leaders have 
said they would oppose any such amendments 
byrd described his proposal as a safety net for up to 5000 
miners who stand to lose their jobs because of tougher controls on 
acid rain pollution caused by emissions from coalburning plants 
it would provide miners with up to four years of full or part 
salary when their job loss is attributed to the new controls 
originally byrd had sought assistance costing nearly 14 
billion over six years but he then cut that in half in a bid to 
gain support nevertheless the administration told senate leaders 
the measure was still too expensive 
if this amendment is passed its over because president 
bush will not support a compromise bill that includes the coal 
miner provision senate minority leader bob dole rkan said 
during debate thursday night the administration doesnt like 
this amendment one bit and that would be an understatement 
mitchell said friday that negotiations were under way among 
senate leaders byrd and the administration to try to work out a 
settlement 
im willing to let the dice roll by putting the matter to a 
vote byrd said 
mitchell had threatened all week to hold the senators in session 
into today if necessary to work out key provisions of the clean air 
legislation but he canceled those plans friday because of the 
impasse over the coal miner assistance issue 
amendments still pending include several that would strengthen 
the pollution controls including those upon automobiles 
several of those measures especially a call for a second round 
of auto emission controls and broader alternative fuels programs 
are opposed by the administration 
mitchell said he hoped the senate could move swiftly when it 
returns march 20 because then we are going to stay on this bill 
until we finish it he said 
