<TEXT>
us military experts today arrived in 
laos to try to recover the remains of american airmen whose planes 
crashed during the vietnam war a spokesman for the us embassy in 
bangkok said 
the 16 americans will work with laotian specialists in 
excavating the area in southern laos where march 1989 survey 
found evidence that it may yield the remains of americans 
missing in action said the spokesman james williams 
the joint excavation will take 23 weeks he said quoting a 
pentagon statement us and laotian specialists also will conduct 
surveys at several other sites during this time he said 
the 16 americans are from the us joint casualty resolution 
center and the army central identification laboratory hawaiibased 
units entrusted with accounting for americas wartime missing 
in january another joint excavation in communist laos recovered 
remains that are still being analyzed williams said 
williams said 2304 americans are listed as missing from the 
vietnam war which also involved fighting in neighboring laos and 
cambodia 
of those 1679 are missing in vietnam 537 in laos 82 in 
cambodia and six in coastal waters off china 
on tuesday us and vietnamese specialists completed a joint 
search in five northern vietnamese provinces for information on 12 
missing american airmen the official vietnam news agency reported 
it did not say if anything was found 
</TEXT>
