<TEXT>
democrats in congress are zeroing in on the 
richgetricher argument as they battle president bushs proposal 
to cut taxes on capital gains 
changes in federal tax laws since 1977 have shifted considerably 
more of the tax burden away from the wealthiest taxpayers and a 
capitalgains cut would worsen the inequity the congressional 
budget office says in a new report 
in releasing the study friday rep dan rostenkowski dill 
chairman of the house ways and means committee described as 
staggering the tax shift and the increases in incomes of the 
richest americans 
the nonpartisan cbo estimated that 59 percent of the 
capitalgains tax cut would go to the richest 1 percent of 
americans whose incomes average 162000 the top 5 percent 
averaging almost 59000 would get 85 percent of the reduction 
other analyses by cbo the ways and means committee staff and a 
laborfinanced group citizens for tax justice released in recent 
days reached the same conclusions 
senior aides to rostenkowski said that without such analyses 
the heated debate over cutting taxes on capital gains which are 
profits from the sale of investments would be conducted solely on 
administration claims that the reduction would boost the economy 
and lower the budget deficit 
the administration is not raising the other issue what has 
happened to tax progressivity in the 1980s said one aide who 
like others briefed reporters on condition of anonymity 
progressivity refers to a tax system based on ability to pay 
the aides acknowledged that rostenkowski does not now have the 
votes to defeat a capitalgains tax cut bush has proposed to lower 
the current 28 percent and 33 percent tax rates on capital gains by 
nearly onethird 
meanwhile rostenkowski carried his fight against the cut to a 
convention of securities dealers in boca raton fla he said the 
proposal is neckandneck with a social security tax cut in the 
race for dumbest idea of the year 
i was left nearly speechless by this competition until i 
finally decided to simply call both proposals political junk food 
and just let them go at that rostenkowski said 
