leaders in an article written for sundays editions of the 
washington post he is expected to call once again for a sharp 
increase in the gasoline tax and perhaps for higher taxes on 
tobacco alcohol and crude oil 
the cbo report released friday concluded basically that major 
tax laws enacted in 1978 and 1981 cut taxes significantly for the 
wealthiest americans but not nearly so much for those at other 
income levels 
the conclusion is essentially the same as was reached in a study 
released citizens for tax justice that study found that if the tax 
laws were made as fair today as they were in 1977 all but the 
richest 10 percent would pay less and the government would still 
collect 675 billion a year more 
the bush administration prefers to point out that the richest 
americans are paying a greater share of the total tax burden than 
they were in 1977 congressional economists agree but say the 
reason is that incomes of the wealthiest 10 percent have soared 
during the same period 
