<TEXT>
the energy department is aiming at a june 
restart of production at its rocky flats colo plant the sole 
supplier of plutonium triggers for nuclear weapons 
the plant 16 miles from denver has been closed since last 
november the department ordered safety and management 
improvements although it insists the facility poses no threat to 
public health 
on friday the department said it had approved a restart plan 
submitted by egampg inc which operates rocky flats for the 
government under contract 
the restart plan calls for a phased resumption of plutonium 
production by the end of june with all six plutonium buildings 
back in operation by the end of september 
the announcement did not say exactly when full production would 
be restored although department officials said in late february 
that it probably would be sometime this fall 
catherine kaliniak an energy department spokeswoman said a 
firmer estimate of the restart schedule dates might be announced as 
early as april 
among the improvements that egampg said it will make before 
resuming production are better procedures for verifying safety and 
alarm systems better training new management oversight and an 
environmental compliance review 
implementation of the improvements will be monitored by egampg 
officials and department headquarters officials progress will be 
assessed by an independent oversight board and then energy 
secretary james d watkins will be asked to give the final ok for 
restart 
rocky flats has been plagued by a variety of operating and 
wastehandling problems in recent years last june the fbi raided 
the facility in search of evidence of criminal violations of laws 
governing the handling of radioactive wastes a grand jury was 
impaneled last august but no indictments have been returned 
egampg a longtime weapons industry contractor based in wellesley 
mass officially took over rocky flats on jan 1 from rockwell 
international corp although egampg has been working on a 
plantimprovement strategy since last september rockwell quit 
operating the plant last september in a dispute with watkins over 
legal liability for environmental violations 
