<TEXT>
officials are trying to find dock workers truck 
drivers and others who may have been exposed to an intensely 
radioactive pellet found in cargo shipped from korea to california 
to massachusetts 
there is no need for panic but there certainly is reason for 
concern nuclear regulatory commission spokesman karl abraham 
said friday people could have received significant exposure 
abraham could not say how many people may have been exposed nor 
what radioactive isotope was involved he said the radioactive 
material was used for making xraytype pictures of welds 
structural steels and other industrial objects 
the pellet the size of a pencil eraser was discovered lying 
loose and unshielded in the bottom of a container that was supposed 
to be empty the container was being sent back to a manufacturer 
for reuse in shipping new pellets abraham said 
the pellet was in a shipment of containers that arrived in the 
boston area two weeks ago more than a month after it was sent from 
south korea to los angeles for storage the shipment then was 
trucked from california to pennsylvania maryland and 
massachusetts abraham said 
a preliminary survey of the truck as it arrived at amersham inc 
of burlington revealed some radioactivity and on closer 
examination technicians found 1500 times more radiation within 
six inches of the source abraham said 
he said tests 4 to 6 inches from the pellet found the level of 
radiation to be 150 rems per hour millions of times higher than 
normal background levels 
a rem is a measure of the estimated damage done to living tissue 
by radiation people generally receive about onetenth of a rem or 
100 millirem of radiation annually from natural sources while the 
average american is exposed to an annual dose of 77 millirem from 
medical xrays 
us department of transportation investigators were working 
with the nrc to establish the shipments route and track down dock 
workers cargo handlers truck drivers warehouse managers and 
other people who may have been exposed to the pellet abraham said 
</TEXT>
