members of congress are criticizing the bush 
administration for missing the deadline for setting out regulations 
to ensure the quality and accuracy of all medical laboratory tests 
lawmakers were not appeased by the health care financing 
administrations announcement that final rules to bring 12000 
medical labs under uniform national testing standards would be 
published next week and could take effect after a 60day comment 
period 
by hcfas own estimate there are between 300000 and 600000 
medical testing facilities including labs in physicians offices 
employer health units public health departments blood banks and 
public screening labs most of those would be covered by other 
rules hcfa is drafting but has not yet formally proposed 
it is critical that all laboratories be regulated sen 
brock adams dwash said friday at the joint hearing of the 
senate labor and human resources committee and the governmental 
affairs subcommittee on oversight of government management each 
month the implementation is delayed more cases of cancer go 
undetected more men and women receive erroneous laboratory reports 
and more tragedies result 
gail wilensky head of hcfa told the lawmakers the rules 
covering 12000 labs that receive payments from medicare and 
medicaid will make a tremendous difference in the way those 
labs operate 
she said those rules were already being drafted when congress 
passed a law in 1988 giving hcfa authority to regulate all testing 
labs and directing the agency to have rules in place to implement 
the law by jan 1 1990 
the main reason for the delay in meeting that deadline she 
said was major unexpected dissension within the scientific 
community over the amount of regulation various types of tests 
should require 
she said hcfa expected to propose rules to meet the 1988 law in 
three stages 
