<DOCNO> AP900310-0069 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
legend has it that rembrandt once bet he could 
prepare an etching of the dutch countryside before a friends 
servant could fetch mustard from a nearby village 
rembrandt won the wager according to the frenchman responsible 
for the tale although it was not said how long the waiter took to 
run his errand the old masters spontaneous touch with a normally 
slow and painstaking medium is known and the results can be seen 
sunday through may 20 at washingtons national gallery of art 
the etching sixs bridge is part of the first major 
exhibit devoted to rembrandts landscape prints and drawings the 
etching shows a canal two boats two bushes a church a bridge 
and two men standing on it all on a plate 5 inches by 10 inches 
rembrandt is better known for his oil paintings but only eight 
of his surviving oils are landscapes largely scattered among 
european museums they are not among the 99 works in this exhibit 
though one of them can be seen in another part of the gallery 
etching can be one of the most difficult timeconsuming 
processes lending itself to tightly controlled highly detailed 
works 
the works are begun on metal plates coated with a soft wax 
formula the artist cuts through the mixture with a needle so that 
acid can bite into the resulting scratches on the plate from which 
the etching is later printed rembrandt took prepared plates with 
him during his long walks around the city 
because of its selfimposed narrow scope the exhibit contains 
much of rembrandts most intimate work homely scenes that roused 
his personal interest boats bridges churches towers cottages 
a man rowing a boat and an artist sketching by the road 
this is the story told by edme francois gersaint who made the 
first catalogue of rembrandts works more than 80 years after the 
artist died in 1669 
one overcast day in the year 1645 rembrandt sat down to lunch at 
the country house of his friend jan six later mayor of amsterdam 
when they made a discovery there was no mustard six sent a 
servant to the village 
rembrandt knew how slow servants usually are in his country 
when they reply anstons which means right away they take at 
least half an hour to appear wrote gersaint in one of the few 
stories about the artist 
so rembrandt made the bet 
art history professor cynthia p schneider of georgetown 
university calls the story apocryphal but she added in the 
catalogue for this exhibit that the work was a miracle of artistic 
economy 
the swift and spare strokes of the etching have all the 
freedom of a sketch from life she said 
she also pointed out that it is done from a low viewpoint as if 
the artist were sitting on the ground gersaint said it was the 
scene from the window of the room the two men were in 
a dutch scholar has claimed to identify the church and sixs 
property along the amstel river in the suburbs of amsterdam then 
it was called kleinkostverloren little moneylost how much 
was the bet are those the two friends on the bridge 
the show will not travel elsewhere after closing in washington 
roger mandle the gallerys deputy director said he expected large 
crowds but did not intend to use a ticket system unless they get 
too big for comfortable viewing 
</TEXT>
