the government acknowledged saturday 
that civilian casualties in last weeks coup attempt were almost 
four times higher than originally reported 
government spokesman naqib sameer said 70 more bodies of 
civilians were pulled from the rubble of destroyed buildings 
bringing the death toll to 95 president najib orignally said 25 
civilians died during the fighting tuesday and wednesday 
no figures were released saturday for military casualties a 
western military expert estimated hundreds of officers and elite 
commandos died when afghan warplanes bombed the capital causing 
extensive damage to the city of 2 million 
the military also appeared have suffered heavy material losses 
at least 10 jet fighters and 15 tanks were believed destroyed 
government and diplomatic sources said the government has said it 
shot down three rebel planes 
meanwhile eastern european diplomatic sources and one afghan 
government official provided some insight into the failure of the 
coup which was launched tuesday by defense minister shah nawaz 
tanai a hardline communist 
according to their statements forces from the afghan 
intelligence agency surrounded two renegade tank corps late monday 
amid indications a coup might be attempted this prevented critical 
ground suport for tanai when the assault began tuesday 
one corps was bottled up near pulcharki prison on the outskirts 
of kabul and another tank unit was surrounded behind the defense 
ministry only two tanks from the unit near pulcharki broke free 
tuesday they attacked the military university near the prison but 
were soon destroyed the eastern european source said 
the renegades were limited to air strikes on the capital 
although the strikes were bloody and destructive they were not 
enough to unseat najib 
the trapped tanks coupled with the armys use of destructive 
scud missiles against mutineers appeared to have been central in 
quelling the coup a western diplomat in islamabad said the prompt 
smashing of tanais communications network also hurt the defense 
ministers plot 
by wednesday most of the fighting was over although rebels and 
diplomats in islamabad claimed fighting went on until friday 
on saturday kabul was calm except for two rockets apparently 
fired by moslem rebels who have been fighting the sovietbacked 
