<TEXT>
louie the llama doesnt have to be a 
follower any more the 5monthold 72pound south american 
ruminant had cataracts removed from his right eye in an operation 
that lets him to see for the first time 
dr james clinton the medford veterinarian who performed the 
50minute surgery thursday said louies history suggests the llama 
could not see because he never started any activities with fellow 
animals 
this one always followed clinton said it never led 
louie is recovering at popcorn park zoo home to about 300 
injured or abandoned animals ranging from chickens to deer said 
zoo director john bergmann 
with cataracts the crystalline lens of the eye becomes opaque 
blocking light rays instead of refracting them the surgeon removes 
the lens leaving the cornea the transparent tissue over the front 
of the eyeball 
clinton compared the crystalline lens to a finetuning 
instrument he said its removal results in about 90 percent vision 
clinton an eye specialist whose prior patients have included 
owls and a leopard said louie was his first llama 
clinton operated on just one eye because the surgery prompts a 
release of a protein that causes inflammation most animals can see 
well enough with one eye but louie could get surgery in his left 
eye after 16 weeks clinton said 
bergmann is checking on how louie is faring with eyesight for 
the first time last night it moved away from us for the first 
time when we brought it food bergmann said friday 
</TEXT>
