<TEXT>
here are some significant dates in haitis modern history 
oct 22 1957 francois papa doc duvalier becomes president 
in disputed election 
april 1 1964 duvalier proclaims himself president for life 
april 21 1971 duvalier dies and 19yearold jeanclaude 
baby doc duvalier becomes president 
feb 7 1986 duvalier flees to exile in france after a month 
of antigovernment unrest that leaves more than 50 people dead a 
threeman junta led by duvaliers army chief of staff lt gen 
henri namphy takes power 
oct 19 1986 low participation in first national election in 
30 years for a 41member constituent assembly to write a new 
constitution 
march 29 1987 voters overwhelmingly approve a new 
constitution putting elections for president and national assembly 
in the hands of a civilian election commission 
june 1987 namphys junta tries to take over elections 
haitians take to the streets and soldiers kill at least 30 armed 
demonstrators antigovernment unrest and diplomatic pressure force 
junta to back down 
nov 29 1987 election day assassins protected by the army 
kill at least 34 voters and confiscate ballots the election is 
called off three hours after it begins namphy and junta dissolve 
election commission the united states suspends 78 million in aid 
in protest 
jan 17 1988 leslie manigat a 57yearold university 
professor is elected president in newly scheduled elections few 
haitians vote and most opposition leaders refuse to participate 
june 19 troops storm the national palace deposing manigat and 
replacing him with namphy namphy abolishes the national assembly a 
day later 
sept 17 namphy is ousted in a coup led by noncommissioned 
officers and exiled in the neighboring dominican republic 
sept 18 lt gen prosper avril chief of the presidential 
guard and a former duvalier adviser declares himself president 
march 13 1989 avril partially restores the suspended 1987 
constitution 
march 28 four highranking army officers are reportedly 
accused of drug trafficking and discharged the action comes one 
day after a us official links resumption of us aid to progress 
in stopping the drug trade 
april 2 gunfire breaks out at the presidential palace the 
government later says it has foiled a coup attempt by rebel 
officers the us embassy says loyal presidential guards rescued 
avril as he was being driven away to be deported 
april 3 avril goes on national television to announce the coup 
was unsuccessfull and says powerhungry soldiers were behind it 
april 4 government placates rebel soldiers by releasing and 
deporting three army officers who led the coup attempt against 
avril 
jan 20 1990 lt gen prosper avril declares a 30day state 
of siege after the mysterious killing of an army colonel fifty 
opposition leaders are arrested jailed and reportedly beaten and 
tortured seven political leaders are exiled 
jan 29 the government lifts the state of siege after the 
united states france canada haitis roman catholic bishops and 
the 12member european community condemn the crackdown 
feb 7 the military declares a general amnesty for all 
political prisoners on the fourth anniversary of the fall of jean 
claude duvalier opposition leaders say they will boycott scheduled 
elections unless avril first steps down 
march 5 rosaline vaval an 11yearold schoolgirl studying on 
her porch is killed by stray bullets fired by soldiers during an 
antigovernment demonstration in the provincial town of petit 
goave the killing sparks nationwide protests against avril 
march 10 avril steps down as haitis leader handing power to 
the army chief of staff maj gen herard abraham abraham promises 
a provisional government led by a civilian will be named to 
organize elections 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

