public transport workers in the danube port city of galati 
according to bucharest radio 
the opposition also argued in its letter that may elections 
would hurt the nations agricultural sector by distracting workers 
from the vital spring planting 
however the primary reason for seeking postponement clearly is 
opposition fears that the national salvation front would have an 
unassailable lead in elections as early as may the front has 
dominated romanian politics and government since the december 
revolution 
the 150member front took power during the revolt it 
relinquished only part of its power to a multiparty council of 
national unity in february after the front announced it would run 
candidates in the elections reversing an earlier pledge the 
reversal touched off an outcry from the opposition because the 
front was also organizing the elections 
the front has since styled itself as a political movement rather 
than a ruling body but its members dominate both the government 
and the council which is serving as a parliament until the 
elections 
in his earlier interview with the associated press unteanu 
said if they decide to postpone the elections it will be a 
signal for political instability 
the government needs to have the legitimacy of elections he 
said 
the government is struggling to restructure the economy from the 
centralized staterun communist model to a freeenterprise market 
economy 
