the state department responded by saying it welcomed the intermim 
leaders promise to give way to a panel led by the supreme court 
president in order to arrange elections 
this step by arabahm is in conformity with the spirit of the 
constitution said adam shub state department spokesman 
the department in its human rights report last month linked 
the haitian army to human rights abuses in rural areas and said 
armed bands some possibly traced to remnants of the feared tonton 
macoute militia of the duvalier years had committed a number of 
murders 
and yet the report said human rights abuses perpetrated or 
directed by government leaders were the hallmark of previous 
haitian regimes the avril government avoided the egregious 
violations massacres and politically motivated killings 
characteristic of its predecessors 
this slightly favorable report to congress on haitis record in 
1989 took a nosedive at the start of this year 
in january the avril government imposed a state of siege 
suspending basic civil liberties prominent opposition politicians 
were beaten and deported the bush administration registered its 
outrage within 10 days the ban and censorship of the press was 
lifted constitutional guarantees were revived 
and on feb 7 political prisoners arrested since november were 
released in an amnesty but the state department said the actions 
were insufficient evidence of the avril governments commitment to 
human rights and free elections ambassador alvin adams was 
recalled to washington 
it was amid this reevaluation of us relations with haiti and 
a strategy designed to wrench a positive response from 
portauprince that the latest crisis developed 
reports that mrs avril had taken refuge in washington were not 
confirmed the state department on saturday watched unfolding 
developments in portauprince without a word of comment 
the avril government is the fifth in haiti since jeanclaude 
duvalier fled for france in february 1986 aboard a us air force 
transport his familys 29year rule was replaced by a national 
governing council 
baby doc left haiti with a strong shove from the reagan 
administration though duvalier left a taped message behind 
suggesting he had made the decision himself so a bloodbath 
would be avoided for my people 
we dont want to take too much credit a us official told 
an associated press reporter at the time but yes we did force 
him out and he knows it he knew that sooner or later we would 
make sure that he did leave but we wanted it done in a way that 
would bring about democracy and help prevent another iran or 
nicaragua 
as it turned out haiti became neither democratic nor as 
instable as iran after the departure of the shah haitians gained 
freedom of expression of the press and of association that did not 
exist under the duvaliers but arbitrary arrests continued 
</TEXT>
