<TEXT>
six aids patients taking the experimental 
drug ddi have died of pancreatitis a toxic side effect attributed 
to the drug according to a published report 
the los angeles times reported saturday that the deaths have 
occurred in the five months since the federal government made ddi 
dideoxyinosine available on a limited basis 
five of the dead were among the 8000 patients receiving ddi as 
part of an expanded access program through the food and drug 
administration according to the drugs manufacturer bristolmyers 
squibb co the sixth was one of 700 patients taking part in 
governmentsponsored trials of the drug the times said 
in a news release saturday the fda said officials were aware of 
adverse reactions to the drug including deaths but didnt provide 
further detail the fda said it asked bristolmyers to provide 
detailed information as soon as possible so the agency could 
determine if changes are needed to make the ongoing protocols as 
safe as possible 
the fda also asked the drug company to write doctors caring for 
patients receiving ddi providing them and their patients with the 
best available information about this situation and urging them to 
monitor their patients closely for signs of pancreatitis 
dr anthony s fauci the director of aids activities for the 
national institutes of health told the paper toxic sideeffects 
some of which will be serious were expected 
pancreatitis is an inflammation of the pancreas a digestive 
organ severe inflammation can lead to kidney failure respiratory 
failure and death 
kathryn r bloom a spokeswoman for bristolmyers told the 
times the it hadnt been proven the deaths were caused by ddi 
bloom said there have been 44 reports of pancreatitis including 
the six fatalities 
we are taking this very seriously bloom told the newspaper 
in addition to the letter being prepared for doctors the company 
is studying the affects of dose levels and the length of therapy 
the expanded access program is to make ddi available to patients 
with advanced infections by hiv the virus that causes aids who 
are unqualified to take part in formal research studies this 
includes patients who are medically unable to take azt another 
drug for aids treatment 
when the expanded access to ddi was approved last year eight 
nonfatal cases of pancreatitis had already been reported among 
about 100 aids patients who had received the drug the times said 
citing government statistics 
many of those patients however were receiving far higher does 
of ddi than those approved for widespread experimental use by the 
fda 
</TEXT>
