an iraqi court sentenced a journalist with a 
british newspaper to death on espionage charges saturday and 
ordered a british nurse jailed for 15 years for allegedly helping 
him the foreign office said 
under iraqi law no appeal is allowed 
the journalist iranianborn farzad bazoft of londons weekly 
observer newspaper was arrested in september while investigating 
reports of an explosion at an iraqi military complex the nurse 
daphne parish was accused of helping bazoft by driving him to the 
plant 
bazoft 31 and mrs parish 52 were tried by a revolutionary 
court on charges of committing hostile acts against iraq the 
proceedings which were not open to the public began thursday then 
were adjourned after five hours they resumed for 35 minutes 
saturday the foreign office said 
the defendents were assigned iraqi lawyers but a british 
diplomat was allowed to attend the trial 
there was no indication when the execution of bazoft might be 
carried out the 31yearold stateless iranian has lived in britain 
since 1975 and travels on british documents 
prime minister margaret thatcher was horrified by the severity 
of the sentence against bazoft a foreign office spokesman said 
he said she will appeal to iraqi president saddam hussein for 
clemency on humanitarian grounds 
junior foreign office minister william waldegrave said the 
government was concentrating on the immediate next few hours 
to get the death sentence lifted 
he said the government was considering sending a toplevel 
emissary to baghdad we rule out nothing he said 
the sentences if carried out are bound to have a 
farreaching effect on relations between the two countries 
waldegrave added 
amnesty international appealed for clemency 
the londonbased human rights organization said in a statement 
that it opposes the death penalty in all cases and supports the 
right not to be subjected to cruel inhuman and degrading 
treatment or punishment 
