brought by the state 
the ruling friday concluded a state attorney generals 
pricefixing investigation into the colorado union of physicians 
and surgeons which has more than 100 members 
state attorney general duane woodard said us district judge 
sherman g finesilver barred the organization from acting as a 
collective bargaining unit on behalf of the physicians it 
represents many of whom are in direct competition 
the groups telephone number is unlisted 
a state complaint contended the organization violated federal 
and state antitrust laws by engaging in a pattern of pricefixing 
woodard said the organization with members in denver and 
pueblo is not a bona fide labor union and its physician members 
are not employees 
therefore the collective bargaining done by cups with various 
hospitals and health insurance plans is an illegal restraint of 
trade and amounts to pricefixing he said 
the organization agreed in a settlement of the complaint to pay 
the state 8000 for investigative costs and attorneys fees 
the complaint said the doctors group and its members agreed on 
reimbursement for providing medical services to patients then 
would negotiate for increased compensation with insurance 
companies hospitals and health maintenance organizations 
