<TEXT>
the roman catholic archbishop of los angeles 
has asked elderly nuns and priests to volunteer to be inoculated 
with an experimental aids vaccine 
archbishop roger mahony has sent a letter to the 3500 priests 
and nuns in the los angeles archdiocese seeking 10 volunteers age 
65 or older the prototype vaccine was developed by dr jonas salk 
father of the commercial polio vaccine 
the appeal was first reported by the chicago tribune which said 
some scientists are concerned about the proposed experiment and the 
safety of salks vaccine that is because the prototype vaccine is 
the only one among several being developed that is made from the 
whole aids virus 
critics say that if live strains of the virus contaminate the 
vacine the volunteers could be accidentally infected the paper 
said in its sunday editions 
the main reason for seeking volunteers from the ranks of the 
church was that they presumably would be most unlikely to have been 
infected with aids through the two most common means sexual 
intercourse or intravenous drug use the paper said 
the rev kevin kostelnik who was working saturday night at st 
vibianas church adjacent to mahonys residence said a letter 
requesting volunteers was sent out two months ago 
the letter really didnt go into detail kostelnik said i 
work in the office so i didnt see the need to respond to it 
kostelnik said he couldnt recall the details of the letter but 
that it was sent to all the nuns and priests in los angeles and was 
seeking five to ten volunteers 
mahony is in rome until march 19 kostelnik said 
scores of americans were infected with polio in the early 1950s 
when salk used the same technique in developing the polio vaccine 
that eventually saved thousands of lives 
a government investigation later determined the infections 
resulted when the virus contained in the vaccine hadnt been 
killed as it was supposed to have been 
thus if any of the volunteers were to test positive later for 
the aids virus the infection could be traced directly to live 
virus that had contaminated the vaccine 
the appeal by mahony to the religious community was accompanied 
by a letter in which dr brian henderson of the university of 
southern california said salk would be the first volunteer 
the 75yearold salk works at the la jolla calif institute 
that bears his name 
henderson one of salks collaborators added another reason for 
appealing to priests and nuns the need for individuals who would 
find a role as such a volunteer a meaningful part of their life 
salk said he hasnt inoculated himself or any voluteers because 
the proposed experiment had yet to be approved by california 
authorities the tribune said 
salk developed the first polio vaccine which was pronounced 
safe and effective on april 12 1955 the deadvirus vaccine was 
administered by injection 
in the 1960s an oral polio vaccine was developed by dr albert 
sabin and it has generally replaced the salk vaccine in part 
because of the ease of giving it the vaccine developed by sabin is 
also more potent and longlasting but because it uses tamed live 
virus one of about every 32 million doses results in paralytic 
polio according to the centers for disease control in atlanta 
