<TEXT>
puerto rican nationalists burned 
and stomped on an american flag friday to protest congressional 
hearings on the islands future ties with the united states 
the protest by dozens of independence supporters coincided with 
the first of three days of hearings in san juan by an eightmember 
congressional delegation eighty witnesses are scheduled to testify 
on a proposed referendum in june 1991 on the caribbean islands 
future 
about 100 protesters calling themselves the socialist front 
against the plebiscite carried signs saying no to colonialism 
and independence outside the hearings at the fine arts 
performing center they also sang the puerto rican anthem 
some of the protesters then torched the us flag and stomped on 
it before peacefully dispersing 
voters are to choose whether puerto rico will become the 51st 
state gain independence or take on an enhanced form of 
commonwealth with more autonomy 
the issue of political status is an emotional one on this us 
commonwealth of 33 million people it has virtually dominated 
politics since the island was ceded by spain in 1898 after the 
spanishamerican war 
the 1991 referendum would be the first vote in more than 20 
years on the islands status in a 1967 referendum 60 percent 
voted to continue as a commonwealth 39 percent favored statehood 
and 1 percent backed independence 
under commonwealth status puerto ricans are us citizens 
eligible for military service food stamps and other benefits but 
they dont pay taxes or vote for president 
the hearings by the house insular and international affairs 
subcommittee are chaired by us virgin islands congressional 
delegate ron de lugo 
the hearings are aimed at determining how much each option would 
cost the us treasury whether the vote should be automatically 
binding and whether a simple majority should be enough to adopt a 
given option 
</TEXT>
