federal regulators sold a failed texas savings 
institution friday to a holding company controlled by financier 
ronald o perelman in a deal that will cost the government 890 
million 
the buyer is putting up 10 million 
the resolution trust corp created in august to dispose of 
failed thrifts sold san antonio savings savings association to 
first gibraltar holdings inc 
the holding company already owns first gibraltar bank a 
dallasbased sampl with assets of over 9 billion it was formed in 
1988 from five smaller insolvent sampls in a much criticized bailout 
deal that required 51 billion in federal assistance and favorable 
tax breaks 
the name of the san antonio sampl will be changed to first 
gibraltar bank but it will be maintained as a separate financial 
institution earlier this week the resolution trust corp board 
voted to allow thrifts created in earlier bailouts to bid for newly 
failed sampls 
however because congress has ordered the corporation to review 
the old bailouts the agency is requiring first gibralatar holdings 
to maintain the san antonio institution as a separately capitalized 
entity 
the corporation said first gibraltars proposal was the cheapest 
of seven received the holding company is taking 11 billion of 
san antonios 23 billion in assets it agreed to assume 
responsibility for deposits of 2 billion in 220000 accounts and 
other liabilities of 750 million it is putting up 10 million of 
its own money 
in return the corporation agreed to advance 16 billion to 
first gibraltar the agency is keeping about 11 billion in sour 
loans after those are sold the net expense to the government will 
total an estimated 890 million 
an investor group macandrews amp forbes holdings inc controls 
first gibralatar holdings its investors include perelman and 
revlon inc 
