of monday 
no other details about the employee including his name were 
released 
investigators believe a motor under a subway car became 
dislodged wednesday hitting a switch and sending half the sixcar 
train onto a second set of tracks the fourth car smashed into 
steel support beams killing three passengers and trapping 
survivors 
of 94 injured 10 were still hospitalized friday all in good or 
satisfactory condition hospital officials said 
a 37block stretch of the subway and elevated train line 
remained closed friday with buses ferrying passengers through west 
philadelphia service was expected to resume monday 
in another development lauber said inspectors examined 76 
motors on 19 cars they found 27 pins installed incorrectly in nuts 
that help hold the motors under the cars 
septa has agreed to thoroughly inspect all cars running the 
line lauber said 
the motor that became partially dislodged and was dragged along 
the subway tracks shortly before wednesdays crash should have been 
attached to the car by a long vertical bolt held on by a nut with 
a cotter pin inserted through the bolt and nut 
a horizontal bolt and safety bracket would have been a backup in 
case the vertical bolt came loose but the safety bracket two 
thick steel loops that normally hold a horizontal bolt had worn 
through in two places 
in addition the nut and cotter pin holding the vertical bolt 
onto the car apparently were lost before the crash lauber said 
the safety bracket tore loose and the motor fell he said the 
motor gouged a 1500foot section of railroad ties before hitting 
the crossover switch and jerking the last three cars to a second 
set of tracks lauber said 
the fourth car was peeled open and nearly cut in half by steel 
support beams seven people were trapped including the three who 
died 
ntsb investigators had been told of at least three times once 
during the past six months once from 1980 to 1982 and once in 1975 
when motors broke loose lauber said 
but investigators did not know whether those motors had fallen 
to the tracks ntsb spokesman alan pollock said friday were 
trying to get the exact details he said 
erich vogel chief mechanical officer for septa confirmed that 
bolts had come loose previously but he believed the motors always 
had been caught by the safety brackets 
ive been here since 1985 and we havent lost a motor that i 
know of he said 
