<TEXT>
jack lindsay a prolific australian 
man of letters and lifelong marxist died at his home in the 
english university city of cambridge he was 89 
lindsay who had written edited or translated more than 170 
books died thursday according to his family 
he died peacefully of old age after a good long life his 
dutch wife meta told the associated press on friday 
lindsay came to england in 1926 and never returned to his 
homeland but his reputation during selfimposed exile flourished 
in australia where he was given the title of officer of the order 
of australia in 1981 
his book that year the crisis of marxism was an often 
agonized analysis of failures he perceived in contemporary marxist 
philosophy 
lindsays works included novels plays and poetry literary 
criticism history and biographies of historical figures writers 
and artists as well as translations of classical writers 
mrs lindsay said her husband liked best his biography of the 
english painter jmw turner 
an obituary in the times of london described lindsay as an 
immensely learned man it said his socialist beliefs deprived his 
work of the serious attention it deserves 
lindsay was born in melbourne in 1900 into a literary and 
artistic family he tried to start a literary movement in sydney 
but then emigrated to london there he founded the fanfrolico 
press which published classical translations 
more than 1 million copies of his novels of british life were 
published in translation in the soviet union he was given the 
soviet order of merit in 1968 
lindsay was active in socialist politics in the 1930s and served 
in the signal corps and at the war office during world war ii his 
four volumes of autobiography contain accounts of literary life in 
australia england and france 
he married twice he had a son and daughter with his second 
wife meta waterdrinker who he met at a peace conference in the 
netherlands and married in 1958 their children philip and helen 
survive 
there will be a private family funeral in cambridge on wednesday 
</TEXT>
