<TEXT>
the junk bond kingpin is dead long live the 
junk bond market 
thats the theme that has emerged in many wall street post 
mortems of drexel burnham lambert now that a month has passed 
since the dominant firm in underwriting and trading of 
lowerquality bonds collapsed into bankruptcy proceedings 
on first reaction drexels demise came as a severe blow to the 
junk market by abruptly removing from the scene the chief advocate 
of highyield finance 
participants in the market lost their primary sponsor 
facilitator and cheerleader even greater perhaps was the 
symbolic impact on the faith and trust of junk bond investors 
nevertheless some observers say the junk bond market seems 
very likely to endure once the current storms have passed indeed 
they add the latest developments may actually prove a boon to 
fanciers of junk in its original sense the depressed bonds of 
companies in trouble 
its likely that what weve known as the junk market in recent 
years with its emphasis on takeover bonds is gone say analysts 
at ids financial services inc in minneapolis 
but highyield securities are a legitimate investment and the 
highyield market will emerge from the current situation in some 
form 
in fact the shakeout now occurring should remove some of the 
excesses that have gone on in recent years and result in a market 
that is more fundamentally sound 
perhaps the greatest irony in the current picture observers 
say is that trouble in the new sectors of the junk bond game may 
well expand activity in the earliest form of junk securities 
before drexel came along the junk bond market was largely made 
up of oncerespectable issues that had fallen on hard times though 
some of these offered high and risky yields others held out the 
promise of no current return at all since their issuers were in 
default and making no interest or dividend payments 
investors bought noyield junk bonds just as they would 
depressed common stocks speculating on the chances for a 
turnaround in the issuers fortunes 
in part because of drexels failure we expect to see a steady 
flow of new distressed securities in the coming months says 
george putnam iii in the current edition of the bostonbased 
advisory service the turnaround letter 
there will probably be several highly leveraged companies that 
might have been able to squeak by with drexels help but now will 
not make it 
this kind of firesale merchandise has always appealed to a 
hardy breed of speculators historically all you needed in this 
game was one or two big scores to offset the losses from other 
investments that never come back 
but analysts caution that junk bonds of that kind have always 
been and will continue to be a longshot proposition suitable 
only for people who can afford to absorb losses and be patient 
concludes ids 1990 is a watershed year for the highyield 
market a number of the sources of the markets problems will 
resolve themselves this year if investors begin to feel that deals 
are being made for sound reasons and in a prudent manner they will 
return 
