accommodate icahn and it avoids shareholder lawsuits 
others said the icahnusx arrangement reflects how takeover 
strategists are increasingly relying on shareholder votes to gain 
control of target companies because they can no longer rely on bank 
credit and the junkbond market which has slumped badly because of 
a dearth of buyers and a glut of sellers drexel burnham lambert 
inc the biggest junk underwriter collapsed a month ago 
more than half a dozen large american corporations already are 
facing proxy fights which are efforts by minority shareholders to 
put an issue to a vote at annual meetings the objective is usually 
to sack the directors and replace them with allies who will take 
control or force the companys sale 
the most prominent of these fights is an effort by dallas 
investor harold simmons who owns about 19 percent lockheed corp 
to replace directors up for election with a slate of his own and 
nullify the aerospace giants poison pill antitakeover defense 
other examples include ual corp facing a proxy challenge by 
coniston partners a new yorkbased takeover investment group and 
armstrong world industries inc challenged by the belzbergs a 
wealthy canadian family 
the end of easily available money for takeovers isnt the only 
obstacle confronting the icahns simmonses and belzbergs who were 
once much more aggressive in their tactics corporate management 
has been strengthened by recent court decisions and a number of 
state antitakeover laws 
many takeover strategists are particularly alarmed about a 
proposed strengthening of a pennsylvania law that could serve as a 
model for other states which would require hostile buyers to 
surrender their profits from the sale of an acquired company 
this bill is anticapitalist and would set a dangerous 
precedent with farreaching consequences the dean of the 
takeover strategists t boone pickens wrote recently in the 
newsletter of his washington lobby group the united shareholders 
association with management untouchable by shareholders no 
matter how poorly it performs there will be little incentive for 
anyone to own stock 
in other business and economic news this past week 
new weaknesses surfaced in american manufacturing domestic 
automakers said us car and truck sales fell nearly 8 percent in 
february the lowest showing in seven years while japanese 
automakers strengthened their share of the market the government 
said us factory orders fell 54 percent in january the biggest 
drop in 15 years 
stocks and bonds slumped at the end of the week hurt by 
renewed fear of higher inflation the catalyst for the drop was the 
government report on february unemployment which showed the 
economy produced the most jobs in nearly two years 
the bestknown softdrink makers in the united states and 
france attempted to inject fresh fizz into classic flops cocacola 
co announced the test marketing of coke ii five years after the 
introduction of a marketing debacle new coke perrier which 
recalled its soda water worldwide because of benzene contamination 
announced an ambitious campaign to relaunch it with an ambitious 
sales and advertising campaign 
</TEXT>
