<DOCNO> AP900310-0161 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the municipal bond market could be in for a 
major boost in the coming decade thanks to president bushs new 
national transportation policy 
the policy released this past week calls for shifting much of 
the cost of the nations transportation system to state and local 
governments it also envisions users of the system paying for 
upkeep as much as possible and private investors taking a larger 
role in the funding 
the result experts say should be greater sales of taxexempt 
bonds by state and local governments the historical way that 
highways airports ports and transit systems are paid for 
it will cause a major increase in bond issuance over the next 
decade predicted peter j schmitt chief operating officer of 
financial guaranty insurance co which insures municipal bonds 
other experts are more cautious 
it is the beginning of a process it may take a couple of 
years before you begin to see specific results from it said 
austin koenen chairman of the public securities association a 
trade group for companies that underwrite municipal bonds 
for years many groups including the psa have been saying the 
nations infrastructure roads rails airports and waterways 
needs a major upgrading koenen said bushs plan is a recognition 
of this concern 
the bush policy outlines new ways for state and local 
governments to raise funds for transportation such as airport 
passenger taxes and tolls on roads built with federal funds both 
of which are now prohibited 
koenen said this means the policy should favor the use of 
municipal revenue bonds rather than general obligation bonds 
general obligation bonds are backed by the general taxing authority 
of a government while revenue bonds are tied to a specific revenue 
source linked to the project to be funded such as tolls charged 
for use of a highway built with bonds 
another reason revenue bonds should be more popular than general 
obligation bonds is that raising taxes is a political pitfall for 
most state and local governments legislatures and voters are much 
more willing to approve bond issues if they are paid off by a fee 
tied to the project funded instead of by a general tax on all 
residents 
while the bush plan is encouraging the psa said it will 
continue to press for easing of taxcode rules that it contends 
hinder the issuance of municipal bonds 
schmitt said the plan appears to favor increased use of 
publicprivate partnerships in funding transportation but those 
partnerships were reined in by the 1986 code revision 
you cant have it both ways he said 
the 1986 tax revision reduced the percentage of revenue from a 
municipal bond issue that may benefit private interests from 25 
percent to 10 percent the revision also put caps on each state on 
the amount of taxexempt bond funding they may issue for private 
uses 
the change was made in response to what was perceived to be 
abuse of the taxexempt fundraising ability of local governments 
for the benefit of private companies 
but bob brown a vice president at shearson lehman hutton inc 
said the restriction should be eased for transportation projects 
since transportation traditionally is a function of government 
while the bush policy statement appears to promote municipal 
bonds brown said it is more important as a recognition of the 
needs of the nations transportation system 
the real thing that drives the municipal market is not so much 
federal policy as the need for infrastructure he said what 
will have a much greater effect over the next five years is how 
people begin to look at infrastructure needs do they see that as a 
top priority to address at all levels of government 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

