<TEXT>
coffee futures went from boiling hot on monday when prices went 
over 1 a pound to ice cold on friday when they dropped 700 
points 
technical factors and speculation about brazilian coffee 
supplies helped trigger the lateweek selloff 
everything looked sweet as the week began with concern about 
tight availability of highquality coffee boosting prices on the 
new york coffee sugar and cocoa exchange to eightmonth highs 
coffee futures had fallen below 70 cents a pound last year as 
producers sold out their warehoused stocks but the price moved 
higher as the supplydemand situation became more balanced 
monday was the fourth straight day of strength for the market 
but the advances didnt have anything to do with any fresh news 
traders said 
there was civil strife in the ivory coast a shortfall in 
mexicos coffee supply poor growing conditions in colombia and a 
lack of availability from ecuador but traders essentially already 
known about those factors analysts said 
during the week coffee prices started slipping then on friday 
futures tumbled on talk that brazil was ready to put more of its 
crop on the world market 
marchs futures contract for coffee dipped to 9518 cents a 
pound falling 732 points in monster volume said bert ruiz a 
vice president of balfour maclaine corp 
the brazilian coffee agency estimated thursday that it had over 
16 million bags on hand ruiz said 
although much of that coffee was not apparently of the finer 
exportable grade there apparently was enough to scare traders 
many of whom were speculating coffee had been overbought earlier 
this week when the nearmonth contract topped 105 a pound ruiz 
said 
coffee settled 425 cents to 732 cents lower with the contract 
for delivery in march at 9518 cents 
